</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use as required. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fd/Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-1Bullet4.jpg/v4-459px-Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-1Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fd/Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-1Bullet4.jpg/v4-759px-Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-1Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

This slower method has the benefit of preserving the fragrance of the mushrooms. Place the dried mushrooms in a bowl. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/95/Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/95/Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Cover with cold water. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f0/Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f0/Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Leave for at least 2 hours. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/42/Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/42/Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-2Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use as needed. Cut off any touch thick stems and just use the caps. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/57/Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-2Bullet4.jpg/v4-459px-Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-2Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/57/Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-2Bullet4.jpg/v4-759px-Rehydrate-Dried-Mushrooms-Step-2Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
